[src:jackson-json-java/data-binding] In computer programming, **data-binding** is a general technique that binds data sources from the provider and consumer together and synchronizes them.
[src:jackson-json-java/data-binding] This is usually done with two data/information sources with different languages, as in XML data binding and UI data binding.
[src:jackson-json-java/data-binding] In UI data binding, data and information objects of the same language, but different logic function are bound together (e.g., Java UI elements to Java objects).
[src:jackson-json-java/data-binding] In a data binding process, each data change is reflected automatically by the elements that are bound to the data.
[src:jackson-json-java/data-binding] The term data binding is also used in cases where an outer representation of data in an element changes, and the underlying data is automatically updated to reflect this change.
[src:jackson-json-java/data-binding] As an example, a change in a `TextBox` element could modify the underlying data value.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] In the Java computer programming language, an **annotation** is a form of syntactic metadata that can be added to Java source code, like an attribute.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] Classes, methods, variables, parameters and Java packages may be annotated.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] Like Javadoc tags, Java annotations can be read from source files.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] Unlike Javadoc tags, Java annotations can also be embedded in and read from Java class files generated by the Java compiler.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] This allows annotations to be retained by the Java virtual machine at run-time and read via reflection.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] It is possible to create meta-annotations out of the existing ones in Java.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] The Java platform has various *ad-hoc* annotation mechanisms—for example, the *`transient`* modifier, or the *`@Deprecated`* javadoc tag.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] The Java Specification Request JSR-175 introduced the general-purpose annotation (also known as *metadata*) facility to the Java Community Process in 2002; it gained approval in September 2004.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] Annotations became available in the language itself beginning with version 1.5 of the Java Development Kit (JDK).
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] The `apt` tool provided a provisional interface for compile-time annotation processing in JDK version 1.5; JSR-269 formalized this, and it became integrated into the javac compiler in version 1.6.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] In C++26, C++ added annotations for reflection that are similar to Java annotations.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] Java defines a set of annotations that are built into the language.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] Of the seven standard annotations, three are part of java.lang, and the remaining four are imported from `java.lang.annotation`.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] There was previously an annotation, `@ManagedBean`, located in `jakarta.annotation`, which was historically used to declare a Managed Bean which are container managed objects that support a small set of basic services such as resource injection, lifecycle callbacks and interceptors.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] This example demonstrates the use of the `@Override` annotation.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] It instructs the compiler to check parent classes for matching methods.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] In this case, an error is generated because the `gettype()` method of class Cat doesn't in fact override `getType()` of class Animal like is desired, because of the mismatching case.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] If the `@Override` annotation were absent, a new method of name `gettype()` would be created in class Cat.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] Annotation type declarations are similar to normal interface declarations.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] An at-sign (@) precedes the keyword "interface".
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] Annotations may include a set of key-value pairs, which are modeled as methods of the annotation type.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] Each method declaration defines an element of the annotation type.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] Method declarations must not have any parameters or a throws clause.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] Return types are restricted to primitives, String, Class, enums, annotations, and arrays of the preceding types.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] The compiler reserves a set of special annotations (including `@Deprecated`, `@Override` and `@SuppressWarnings`) for syntactic purposes.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] Annotations are widely used by frameworks as a way of conveniently applying behaviors to user-defined classes and methods that must otherwise be declared in an external source (such as an XML configuration file) or programmatically (with API calls).
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] For instance, the library *Project Lombok* makes extensive usage of annotations to reduce boilerplate.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] The annotations are not method calls and will not, by themselves, do anything.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] Rather, the class object is passed to the Jakarta Persistence implementation at run-time, which then extracts the annotations to generate an object–relational mapping.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] When Java source code is compiled, annotations can be processed by compiler plug-ins called annotation processors.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] Processors can produce informational messages or create additional Java source files or resources, which in turn may be compiled and processed.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] However, annotation processors cannot modify the annotated code itself.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] (Code modifications may be implemented using methods beyond the Java Language Specification.) The Java compiler conditionally stores annotation metadata in the class files, if the annotation has a `RetentionPolicy` of `CLASS` or `RUNTIME`.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] Later, the JVM or other programs can look for the metadata to determine how to interact with the program elements or change their behavior.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] In addition to processing an annotation using an annotation processor, a Java programmer can write their own code that uses reflection to process the annotation.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] Java SE 5 supports a new interface that is defined in the `java.lang.reflect` package.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] This package contains the interface called `AnnotatedElement` that is implemented by the Java reflection classes including `Class`, `Constructor`, `Field`, `Method`, and `Package`.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] The implementations of this interface are used to represent an annotated element of the program currently running in the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] This interface allows annotations to be read reflectively.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] The `AnnotatedElement` interface provides access to annotations having `RUNTIME` retention.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] This access is provided by the `getAnnotation`, `getAnnotations`, and `isAnnotationPresent` methods.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] Because annotation types are compiled and stored in byte code files just like classes, the annotations returned by these methods can be queried just like any regular Java object.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-annotation] Libraries such as JUnit use annotation processing to generate unit tests.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Java gained popularity shortly after its release, and has been a popular programming language since then.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Java was the third most popular programming language in 2022 according to GitHub.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Although still widely popular, there has been a gradual decline in use of Java in recent years with other languages using JVM gaining popularity.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Java was designed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] It was released in May 1995 as a core component of Sun's Java platform.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The original and reference implementation Java compilers, virtual machines (VMs), and class libraries were released by Sun under proprietary licenses.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] As of May 2007, in compliance with the specifications of the Java Community Process, Sun had relicensed most of its Java technologies under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Oracle, which bought Sun in 2010, offers its own HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] However, the official reference implementation is the OpenJDK JVM, which is open-source software used by most developers and is the default JVM for almost all Linux distributions.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] As of March 2026, Java 26 is the current version.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton initiated the Java language project in June 1991.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Java was originally designed for interactive television, but it was too advanced for the digital cable television industry at the time.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The language was initially called *Oak* after an oak tree that stood outside Gosling's office.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Later the project went by the name *Green* and was finally renamed *Java*, from Java coffee, a type of coffee from Indonesia.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Gosling designed Java with a C/C++-style syntax that system and application programmers would find familiar.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Sun Microsystems released the first public implementation as Java 1.0 in 1996.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] It promised write once, run anywhere (WORA) functionality, providing no-cost run-times on popular platforms.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Fairly secure and featuring configurable security, it allowed network- and file-access restrictions.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Major web browsers soon incorporated the ability to run Java applets within web pages, and Java quickly became popular.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The Java 1.0 compiler was re-written in Java by Arthur van Hoff to comply strictly with the Java 1.0 language specification.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] With the advent of Java 2 (released initially as J2SE 1.2 in December 1998 – 1999), new versions had multiple configurations built for different types of platforms.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] J2EE included technologies and APIs for enterprise applications typically run in server environments, while J2ME featured APIs optimized for mobile applications.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] In 2006, for marketing purposes, Sun renamed new J2 versions as *Java EE*, *Java ME*, and *Java SE*, respectively.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] In 1997, Sun Microsystems approached the ISO/IEC JTC 1 standards body and later the Ecma International to formalize Java, but it soon withdrew from the process.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Java remains a *de facto* standard, controlled through the Java Community Process.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] At one time, Sun made most of its Java implementations available without charge, despite their proprietary software status.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Sun generated revenue from Java through the selling of licenses for specialized products such as the Java Enterprise System.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] On November 13, 2006, Sun released much of its Java virtual machine (JVM) as free and open-source software (FOSS), under the terms of the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] On May 8, 2007, Sun finished the process, making all of its JVM's core code available under free software/open-source distribution terms, aside from a small portion of code to which Sun did not hold the copyright.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Sun's vice-president Rich Green said that Sun's ideal role with regard to Java was as an *evangelist*.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Following Oracle Corporation's acquisition of Sun Microsystems in 2009–10, Oracle has described itself as the steward of Java technology with a relentless commitment to fostering a community of participation and transparency.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] This did not prevent Oracle from filing a lawsuit against Google shortly after that for using Java inside the Android SDK (see the *Android* section).
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] On April 2, 2010, James Gosling resigned from Oracle.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] In January 2016, Oracle announced that Java run-time environments based on JDK 9 will discontinue the browser plugin.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Java software runs on most devices from laptops to data centers, game consoles to scientific supercomputers.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Oracle (and others) highly recommend uninstalling outdated and unsupported versions of Java, due to unresolved security issues in older versions.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] It must be architecture-neutral and portable.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] It must be interpreted, threaded, and dynamic.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] As of June 2026, Java 8, 11, 17, 21, and 25 are supported as long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Oracle released the last zero-cost public update for the legacy version Java 8 LTS in January 2019 for commercial use, although it will otherwise still support Java 8 with public updates for personal use indefinitely.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Other vendors such as Adoptium continue to offer free builds of OpenJDK's long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] These builds may include additional security patches and bug fixes.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Sun has defined and supports four editions of Java targeting different application environments and segmented many of its APIs so that they belong to one of the platforms.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The classes in the Java APIs are organized into separate groups called packages.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Each package contains a set of related interfaces, classes, subpackages and exceptions.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Sun also provided an edition called Personal Java that has been superseded by later, standards-based Java ME configuration-profile pairings.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] One design goal of Java is portability, which means that programs written for the Java platform must run similarly on any combination of hardware and operating system with adequate run time support.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] This is achieved by compiling the Java language code to an intermediate representation called JVM bytecode, instead of directly to architecture-specific machine code.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] JVM bytecode instructions are analogous to machine code, but they are intended to be executed by a virtual machine (VM) written specifically for the host hardware.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] End-users commonly use a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) installed on their device for standalone Java applications or a web browser for Java applets.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Standard libraries provide a generic way to access host-specific features such as graphics, threading, and networking.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The use of universal bytecode makes porting simple.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] However, the overhead of interpreting bytecode into machine instructions made interpreted programs almost always run more slowly than native executables.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Just-in-time (JIT) compilers that compile byte-codes to machine code during runtime were introduced from an early stage.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Java's Hotspot compiler is actually two compilers in one, with GraalVM (included in e.g.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Java 11, but removed as of Java 16) allowing tiered compilation.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Java itself is platform-independent and is adapted to the particular platform it is to run on by a Java virtual machine (JVM), which translates the JVM bytecode into the platform's machine language.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Programs written in Java have a reputation for being slower and requiring more memory than those written in C++.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] With Java 1.5, the performance was improved with the addition of the `java.util.concurrent` package, including lock-free implementations of the ConcurrentMaps and other multi-core collections, and it was improved further with Java 1.6.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Java uses an automatic garbage collector to manage memory in the object lifecycle.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The programmer determines when objects are created, and the Java runtime is responsible for recovering the memory once objects are no longer in use.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Once no references to an object remain, the unreachable memory becomes eligible to be freed automatically by the garbage collector.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Something similar to a memory leak may still occur if a programmer's code holds a reference to an object that is no longer needed, typically when objects that are no longer needed are stored in containers that are still in use.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] If methods for a non-existent object are called, a null pointer exception is thrown.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] One of the ideas behind Java's automatic memory management model is that programmers can be spared the burden of having to perform manual memory management.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] In some languages, memory for the creation of objects is implicitly allocated on the stack or explicitly allocated and deallocated from the heap.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] In the latter case, the responsibility of managing memory resides with the programmer.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] If the program does not deallocate an object, a memory leak occurs.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] If the program attempts to access or deallocate memory that has already been deallocated, the result is undefined and difficult to predict, and the program is likely to become unstable or crash.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] This can be partially remedied by the use of smart pointers, but these add overhead and complexity.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Garbage collection does not prevent logical memory leaks, i.e. those where the memory is still referenced but never used.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Garbage collection may happen at any time.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Ideally, it will occur when a program is idle.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] It is guaranteed to be triggered if there is insufficient free memory on the heap to allocate a new object; this can cause a program to stall momentarily.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Explicit memory management is not possible in Java, however it is possible to make the JVM do garbage collection manually.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Java does not support C/C++ style pointer arithmetic, where object addresses can be arithmetically manipulated (e.g. by adding or subtracting an offset).
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] This allows the garbage collector to relocate referenced objects and ensures type safety and security.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] As in C++ and some other object-oriented languages, variables of Java's primitive data types are either stored directly in fields (for objects) or on the stack (for methods) rather than on the heap, as is commonly true for non-primitive data types (but see escape analysis).
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] This was a conscious decision by Java's designers for performance reasons.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Java contains multiple types of garbage collectors.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Since Java 9, HotSpot uses the Garbage First Garbage Collector (G1GC) as the default.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] However, there are also several other garbage collectors that can be used to manage the heap, such as the Z Garbage Collector (ZGC) introduced in Java 11, and Shenandoah GC, introduced in Java 12 but unavailable in Oracle-produced OpenJDK builds.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Shenandoah is instead available in third-party builds of OpenJDK, such as Eclipse Temurin.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] For most applications in Java, G1GC is sufficient.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] In prior versions of Java, such as Java 8, the Parallel Garbage Collector was used as the default garbage collector.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Having solved the memory management problem does not relieve the programmer of the burden of handling properly other kinds of resources, like network or database connections, file handles, etc., especially in the presence of exceptions.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The syntax of Java is largely influenced by C++ and C.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, which combines the syntax for structured, generic, and object-oriented programming, Java was built almost exclusively as an object-oriented language.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] All code is written inside classes, and every data item is an object, with the exception of the primitive data types, (i.e. integers, floating-point numbers, boolean values, and characters), which are not objects for performance reasons.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, Java does not support operator overloading or multiple inheritance for classes, though multiple inheritance is supported for interfaces.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Java uses comments similar to those of C++.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] There are three different styles of comments: a single line style marked with two slashes (`//`), a multiple line style opened with `/*` and closed with `*/`, and the Javadoc commenting style opened with `/**` and closed with `*/`.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The Javadoc style of commenting allows the user to run the Javadoc executable to create documentation for the program and can be read by some integrated development environments (IDEs) such as Eclipse to allow developers to access documentation within the IDE.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Java applets were programs embedded in other applications, mainly in web pages displayed in web browsers.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The Java applet API was deprecated with the release of Java 9 in 2017.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Java servlet technology provides Web developers with a simple, consistent mechanism for extending the functionality of a Web server and for accessing existing business systems.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Servlets are server-side Java EE components that generate responses to requests from clients.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Most of the time, this means generating HTML pages in response to HTTP requests, although there are a number of other standard servlet classes available, for example for WebSocket communication.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Typical implementations of these APIs on Application Servers or Servlet Containers use a standard servlet for handling all interactions with the HTTP requests and responses that delegate to the web service methods for the actual business logic.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] JavaServer Pages (JSP) are server-side Java EE components that generate responses, typically HTML pages, to HTTP requests from clients.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] JSPs embed Java code in an HTML page by using the special delimiters `<%` and `%>`.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] A JSP is compiled to a Java *servlet*, a Java application in its own right, the first time it is accessed.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] After that, the generated servlet creates the response.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Swing is a graphical user interface library for the Java SE platform.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] It is possible to specify a different look and feel through the pluggable look and feel system of Swing.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Clones of Windows, GTK+, and Motif are supplied by Sun.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Apple also provides an Aqua look and feel for macOS.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Where prior implementations of these looks and feels may have been considered lacking, Swing in Java SE 6 addresses this problem by using more native GUI widget drawing routines of the underlying platforms.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] JavaFX is a software platform for creating and delivering desktop applications, as well as rich web applications that can run across a wide variety of devices.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] JavaFX is intended to replace Swing as the standard graphical user interface (GUI) library for Java SE, but since JDK 11 JavaFX has not been in the core JDK and is instead available as a separate module.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] JavaFX has support for desktop computers and web browsers on Microsoft Windows, Linux, and macOS.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] JavaFX does not have support for native OS look and feels.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] In 2004, generics were added to the Java language, as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Prior to the introduction of generics, each variable declaration had to be of a specific type.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] For container classes, for example, this is a problem because there is no easy way to create a container that accepts only specific types of objects.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Either the container operates on all subtypes of a class or interface, usually `Object`, or a different container class has to be created for each contained class.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Generics allow compile-time type checking without having to create many container classes, each containing almost identical code.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] In addition to enabling more efficient code, certain runtime exceptions are prevented from occurring, by issuing compile-time errors.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] If Java prevented all runtime type errors (`ClassCastException`s) from occurring, it would be type safe.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] In 2016, the type system of Java was proven unsound in that it is possible to use generics to construct classes and methods that allow assignment of an instance of one class to a variable of another unrelated class.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Such code is accepted by the compiler, but fails at run time with a class cast exception.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Criticisms directed at Java include the implementation of generics, speed, the handling of unsigned numbers, the implementation of floating-point arithmetic, and a history of security vulnerabilities in the primary Java VM implementation HotSpot.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Developers have criticized the complexity and verbosity of the Java Persistence API (JPA), a standard part of Java EE.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] This has led to increased adoption of higher-level abstractions like Spring Data JPA, which aims to simplify database operations and reduce boilerplate code.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The growing popularity of such frameworks suggests limitations in the standard JPA implementation's ease-of-use for modern Java development.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The Java Class Library is the standard library, developed to support application development in Java.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] It is controlled by Oracle in cooperation with others through the Java Community Process program.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Companies or individuals participating in this process can influence the design and development of the APIs.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] This process has been a subject of controversy during the 2010s.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Javadoc is a comprehensive documentation system, created by Sun Microsystems.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] It provides developers with an organized system for documenting their code.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Javadoc comments have an extra asterisk at the beginning, i.e. the delimiters are `/**` and `*/`, whereas the normal multi-line comments in Java are delimited by `/*` and `*/`, and single-line comments start with `//`.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Oracle Corporation owns the official implementation of the Java SE platform, due to its acquisition of Sun Microsystems on January 27, 2010.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] This implementation is based on the original implementation of Java by Sun.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The Oracle implementation is available for Windows, macOS, Linux, and Solaris.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Because Java lacks any formal standardization recognized by Ecma International, ISO/IEC, ANSI, or other third-party standards organizations, the Oracle implementation is the de facto standard.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Oracle has also released GraalVM, a high performance Java dynamic compiler and interpreter.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] OpenJDK is another Java SE implementation that is licensed under the GNU GPL.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The implementation started when Sun began releasing the Java source code under the GPL.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] As of Java SE 7, OpenJDK is the official Java reference implementation.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The goal of Java is to make all implementations of Java compatible.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Historically, Sun's trademark license for usage of the Java brand insists that all implementations be *compatible*.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] This resulted in a legal dispute with Microsoft after Sun claimed that the Microsoft implementation did not support Java remote method invocation (RMI) or Java Native Interface (JNI) and had added platform-specific features of their own.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Sun sued in 1997, and, in 2001, won a settlement of US$20 million, as well as a court order enforcing the terms of the license from Sun.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] As a result, Microsoft no longer ships Java with Windows.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Platform-independent Java is essential to Java EE, and an even more rigorous validation is required to certify an implementation.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] This environment enables portable server-side applications.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The Java programming language requires the presence of a software platform in order for compiled programs to be executed.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Oracle supplies the Java platform for use with Java.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The Android SDK is an alternative software platform, used primarily for developing Android applications with its own GUI system.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The Java language is a key pillar in Android, an open source mobile operating system.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Although Android, built on the Linux kernel, is written largely in C, the Android SDK uses the Java language as the basis for Android applications but does not use any of its standard GUI, SE, ME or other established Java standards.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The bytecode language supported by the Android SDK is incompatible with JVM bytecode and runs on its own virtual machine, optimized for low-memory devices such as smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Depending on the Android version, the bytecode is either interpreted by the Dalvik virtual machine or compiled into native code by the Android Runtime.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Android does not provide the full Java SE standard library, although the Android SDK does include an independent implementation of a large subset of it.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] It supports Java 6 and some Java 7 features, offering an implementation compatible with the standard library (Apache Harmony).
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] The use of Java-related technology in Android led to a legal dispute between Oracle and Google.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] On May 7, 2012, a San Francisco jury found that if APIs could be copyrighted, then Google had infringed Oracle's copyrights by the use of Java in Android devices.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] District Judge William Alsup ruled on May 31, 2012, that APIs cannot be copyrighted, but this was reversed by the United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit in May 2014.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] On May 26, 2016, the district court decided in favor of Google, ruling the copyright infringement of the Java API in Android constitutes fair use.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] In March 2018, this ruling was overturned by the Appeals Court, which sent down the case of determining the damages to federal court in San Francisco.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] Google filed a petition for writ of certiorari with the Supreme Court of the United States in January 2019 to challenge the two rulings that were made by the Appeals Court in Oracle's favor.
[src:jackson-json-java/java-programming-language] On April 5, 2021, the Court ruled 6–2 in Google's favor, that its use of Java APIs should be considered fair use.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:jackson-json-java/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:jackson-json-java/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:jackson-json-java/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:jackson-json-java/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:jackson-json-java/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:jackson-json-java/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:jackson-json-java/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:jackson-json-java/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:jackson-json-java/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] In computer science, **marshalling** or **marshaling** (US spelling) is the process of transforming the memory representation of an object into a data format suitable for storage or transmission, especially between different runtimes.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] It is typically used when data must be moved between different parts of a computer program or from one program to another.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling simplifies complex communications, because it allows using *composite objects* instead of being restricted to *primitive objects*.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling is sometimes used as synonymous with serializing, while serialization is actually one step in the process of marshalling an object.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling and serialization might thus be done differently, although some form of serialization is usually used to do marshalling.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] The term *deserialization* is somewhat similar to *un*-marshalling a dry object "on the server side", i.e., demarshalling (or unmarshalling) to get a live object back: the serialized object is transformed into an internal data structure, i.e., a live object within the target runtime.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] It usually corresponds to the exact inverse process of marshalling, although sometimes both ends of the process trigger specific business logic.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] The accurate definition of marshalling differs across programming languages such as Python, Java, and .NET, and in some contexts, is used interchangeably with serialization.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] To "serialize" an object means to convert its state into a byte stream in such a way that the byte stream may be converted back into a copy of the object, which is unmarshalling in essence.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] Different programming languages either make or don’t make the distinction between the two concepts.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] In the Java-related RFC 2713, marshalling is used when serializing objects for remote invocation.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] An object that is marshalled records the state of the original object and it contains the codebase (*codebase* here refers to a list of URLs where the object code can be loaded from, and not source code).
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] Hence, in order to convert the object state and codebase(s), unmarshalling must be done.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshaller interface automatically converts the marshalled data containing codebase(s) into an executable Java object in JAXB.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] Any object that can be deserialized can be unmarshalled.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling is used within implementations of different remote procedure call (RPC) mechanisms, where it is necessary to transport data between processes and/or between threads.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] In Microsoft's Component Object Model (COM), interface pointers must be marshalled when crossing COM apartment boundaries.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] In the .NET Framework, the conversion between an unmanaged type and a CLR type, as in the P/Invoke process, is also an example of an action that requires marshalling to take place.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] Additionally, marshalling is used extensively within scripts and applications that use the XPCOM technologies provided within the Mozilla application framework.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] The Mozilla Firefox browser is a popular application built with this framework, that additionally allows scripting languages to use XPCOM through XPConnect (Cross-Platform Connect).
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] In the Microsoft Windows family of operating systems the entire set of device drivers for Direct3D are kernel-mode drivers.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] The user-mode portion of the API is handled by the DirectX runtime provided by Microsoft.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] This is an issue because calling kernel-mode operations from user-mode requires performing a system call, and this inevitably forces the CPU to switch to "kernel mode".
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] This is a slow operation, taking on the order of microseconds to complete.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] During this time, the CPU is unable to perform any operations.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] As such, minimizing the number of times this switching operation must be performed would optimize performance to a substantive degree.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] Linux OpenGL drivers are split in two: a kernel-driver and a user-space driver.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] The user-space driver does all the translation of OpenGL commands into machine code to be submitted to the GPU.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] To reduce the number of system calls, the user-space driver implements marshalling.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] If the GPU's command buffer is full of rendering data, the API could simply store the requested rendering call in a temporary buffer and, when the command buffer is close to being empty, it can perform a switch to kernel-mode and add a number of stored commands all at once.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling data requires some kind of data transfer, which leverages a specific data format to be chosen as the serialization target.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] XML is one such format and means of transferring data between systems.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] Microsoft, for example, uses it as the basis of the file formats of the various components (Word, Excel, Access, PowerPoint, etc.) of the Microsoft Office suite (see Office Open XML).
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] While this typically results in a verbose wire format, XML's fully-bracketed "start-tag", "end-tag" syntax allows provision of more accurate diagnostics and easier recovery from transmission or disk errors.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] In addition, because the tags occur repeatedly, one can use standard compression methods to shrink the content—all the Office file formats are created by zipping the raw XML.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] Alternative formats such as JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) are more concise, but correspondingly less robust for error recovery.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] Once the data is transferred to a program or an application, it needs to be converted back to an object for usage.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] Hence, unmarshalling is generally used in the receiver end of the implementations of Remote Method Invocation (RMI) and Remote procedure call (RPC) mechanisms to unmarshal transmitted objects in an executable form.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] JAXB or Java Architecture for XML Binding is the most common framework used by developers to marshal and unmarshal Java objects.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] JAXB provides for the interconversion between fundamental data types supported by Java and standard XML schema data types.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] `System.Xml.Serialization.XmlSerializer` is the framework used by C# developers to marshal and unmarshal C# objects.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] One of the advantages of C# over Java is that C# natively supports marshalling due to the inclusion of `System.Xml.Serialization.XmlSerializer` class.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] Java, on the other hand requires a non-native glue code in the form of JAXB to support marshalling.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] An example of unmarshalling is the conversion of an XML representation of an object to the default representation of the object in any programming language.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] Unmarshalling is the process of converting the XML representation to the default executable Java representation, and running that very code to get a consistent, live object back.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] Had a different format been chosen, the unmarshalling process would have been different, but the end result in the target runtime would be the same.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] The process of unmarshalling XML data into an executable Java object is taken care of by the in-built `jakarta.xml.bind.Unmarshaller` (formally `javax.xml.bind.Unmarshaller`) class.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal methods defined in the `jakarta.xml.bind.Unmarshaller` class are overloaded to accept XML from different types of input such as a `java.io.File`, `java.io.FileInputStream`, or `java.net.URL`.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] Unmarshal methods can deserialize an entire XML document or a small part of it.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] When the XML root element is globally declared, these methods utilize the `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext`'s mapping of XML root elements to JAXB mapped classes to initiate the unmarshalling.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] If the mappings are not sufficient and the root elements are declared locally, the unmarshal methods use `declaredType` methods for the unmarshalling process.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] These two approaches can be understood below.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal method uses `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext` (formerly `javax.xml.bind.JAXBContext`) to unmarshal the XML data, when the root element is globally declared.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] The `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext` object always maintains a mapping of the globally declared XML element and its name to a JAXB mapped class.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] If the XML element name or its `@xsi:type` attribute matches the JAXB mapped class, the unmarshal method transforms the XML data using the appropriate JAXB mapped class.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] However, if the XML element name has no match, the unmarshal process will abort and throw an `jakarta.xml.bind.UnmarshalException` (formerly `javax.xml.bind.UnmarshalException`).
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] This can be avoided by using the unmarshal by `declaredType` methods.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] When the root element is not declared globally, the application assists the unmarshaller by application-provided mapping using `declaredType` parameters.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] By an order of precedence, even if the root name has a mapping to an appropriate JAXB class, the `declaredType` overrides the mapping.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] However, if the `@xsi:type` attribute of the XML data has a mapping to an appropriate JAXB class, then this takes precedence over declaredType parameter.
[src:jackson-json-java/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal methods by `declaredType` parameters always return a `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBElement<T>` instance.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
