[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] The core general serialization mechanism is the `pickle` standard library module, alluding to the database systems term *pickling* to describe data serialization (*unpickling* for *deserializing*).
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] Pickle uses a simple stack-based virtual machine that records the instructions used to reconstruct the object.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] It is a cross-version customizable but unsafe (not secure against erroneous or malicious data) serialization format.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] Malformed or maliciously constructed data, may cause the deserializer to import arbitrary modules and instantiate any object.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] The standard library also includes modules serializing to standard data formats: `json` (with built-in support for basic scalar and collection types and able to support arbitrary types via encoding and decoding hooks).
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] `plistlib` (with support for both binary and XML property list formats).
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] `xdrlib` (with support for the External Data Representation (XDR) standard as described in RFC 1014).
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] Finally, it is recommended that an object's `__repr__` be evaluable in the right environment, making it a rough match for Common Lisp's `print-object`.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] Not all object types can be pickled automatically, especially ones that hold operating system resources like file handles, but users can register custom "reduction" and construction functions to support the pickling and unpickling of arbitrary types.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] Pickle was originally implemented as the pure Python `pickle` module, but, in versions of Python prior to 3.0, the `cPickle` module (also a built-in) offers improved performance (up to 1000 times faster).
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] The `cPickle` was adapted from the Unladen Swallow project.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] In Python 3, users should always import the standard version, which attempts to import the accelerated version and falls back to the pure Python version.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] R has the function `dput` which writes an ASCII text representation of an R object to a file or connection.
