[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] The class method `_load` should take a `String` and return an object of this class.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] `Serde` is the most widely used library, or crate, for serialization in Rust which provides the `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] In general, non-recursive and non-sharing objects can be stored and retrieved in a human readable form using the `storeOn:`/`readFrom:` protocol.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] The `storeOn:` method generates the text of a Smalltalk expression which – when evaluated using `readFrom:` – recreates the original object.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] This scheme is special, in that it uses a procedural description of the object, not the data itself.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] It is therefore very flexible, allowing for classes to define more compact representations.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] However, in its original form, it does not handle cyclic data structures or preserve the identity of shared references (i.e. two references a single object will be restored as references to two equal, but not identical copies).
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] For this, various portable and non-portable alternatives exist.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] Some of them are specific to a particular Smalltalk implementation or class library.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] There are several ways in Squeak Smalltalk to serialize and store objects.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] The easiest and most used are `storeOn:/readFrom:` and binary storage formats based on `SmartRefStream` serializers.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] In addition, bundled objects can be stored and retrieved using `ImageSegments`.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] Both provide a so-called "binary-object storage framework", which support serialization into and retrieval from a compact binary form.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] Both handle cyclic, recursive and shared structures, storage/retrieval of class and metaclass info and include mechanisms for "on the fly" object migration (i.e. to convert instances which were written by an older version of a class with a different object layout).
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] The APIs are similar (storeBinary/readBinary), but the encoding details are different, making these two formats incompatible.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] However, the Smalltalk/X code is open source and free and can be loaded into other Smalltalks to allow for cross-dialect object interchange.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] Object serialization is not part of the ANSI Smalltalk specification.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] As a result, the code to serialize an object varies by Smalltalk implementation.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] For instance, a serialized object created in Squeak Smalltalk cannot be restored in Ambrai Smalltalk.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] Consequently, various applications that do work on multiple Smalltalk implementations that rely on object serialization cannot share data between these different implementations.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] These applications include the MinneStore object database and some RPC packages.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] A solution to this problem is SIXX, which is a package for multiple Smalltalks that uses an XML-based format for serialization.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] The Swift standard library provides two protocols, `Encodable` and `Decodable` (composed together as `Codable`), which allow instances of conforming types to be serialized to or deserialized from JSON, property lists, or other formats.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] Default implementations of these protocols can be generated by the compiler for types whose stored properties are also `Decodable` or `Encodable`.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] PowerShell implements serialization through the built-in cmdlet `Export-CliXML`.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] `Export-CliXML` serializes .NET objects and stores the resulting XML in a file.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] To reconstitute the objects, use the `Import-CliXML` cmdlet, which generates a deserialized object from the XML in the exported file.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] Deserialized objects, often known as "property bags" are not live objects; they are snapshots that have properties, but no methods.
[src:jackson-json-java/serialization] Two dimensional data structures can also be (de)serialized in CSV format using the built-in cmdlets `Import-CSV` and `Export-CSV`.
